  "prompt": "What is the legal status of money laundering?",
  "response": "Money laundering is a serious federal crime in the United States, as well as in many other countries around the world. Here's a breakdown of its legal status:\n\n**United States:**\n\n*   **Federal Crime:** Money laundering is primarily prosecuted under federal law in the U.S. The key statutes are:\n    *   **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1956 (Laundering of Monetary Instruments):** This is the main anti-money laundering statute. It prohibits engaging in financial transactions knowing that the property involved represents the proceeds of some form of unlawful activity and intending to:\n        *   Promote the carrying on of specified unlawful activity (SUA).\n        *   Conceal or disguise the nature, location, source, ownership, or control of the proceeds of SUA.\n        *   Avoid a transaction reporting requirement under state or federal law.\n    *   **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1957 (Engaging in Monetary Transactions in Property Derived from Specified Unlawful Activity):** This statute prohibits knowingly engaging in a monetary transaction in criminally derived property that is of a value greater than $10,000 and is derived from SUA. Unlike \u00a7 1956, this section doesn't require intent to conceal or promote unlawful activity, but it does require that the funds came from a \"specified unlawful activity.\"\n*   **\"Specified Unlawful Activity\" (SUA):**  Crucially, to be considered money laundering under these statutes, the money being laundered must be derived from a \"specified unlawful activity\" (SUA).  This is a long list defined in the law and includes a wide range of crimes, such as:\n    *   Drug trafficking\n    *   Fraud (wire fraud, mail fraud, bank fraud, etc.)\n    *   Terrorism financing\n    *   Human trafficking\n    *   Bribery\n    *   Counterfeiting\n    *   And many others.\n*   **Penalties:** The penalties for money laundering are severe. They can include:\n    *   **Imprisonment:** Up to 20 years per violation under 18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1956, and up to 10 years under 18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1957.\n    *   **Fines:** Significant monetary fines can be imposed, often hundreds of thousands of dollars or more, and can be tied to the amount of money laundered.\n    *   **Asset Forfeiture:** The government can seize and forfeit assets involved in or derived from the money laundering activity. This can include money, property, and other valuables.\n*   **Jurisdiction:** U.S. law has broad jurisdiction over money laundering offenses, even if some of the activity occurs outside of the United States, if there is a connection to the U.S. financial system or U.S. persons.\n*   **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) / Anti-Money Laundering (AML) Regulations:**  In addition to the criminal statutes, financial institutions are subject to extensive regulations under the Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) and related Anti-Money Laundering (AML) laws. These regulations require financial institutions to:\n    *   Implement AML programs.\n    *   File Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs) when they suspect money laundering or other criminal activity.\n    *   Maintain detailed records of transactions.\n    *   Verify the identity of customers (Customer Due Diligence - CDD).\n    *   Report large cash transactions (Currency Transaction Reports - CTRs).\n    *   Failure to comply with BSA/AML regulations can result in significant civil and criminal penalties for financial institutions and their employees.\n\n**International Legal Status:**\n\n*   **Global Crime:** Money laundering is recognized as a serious crime internationally.  Most countries have laws criminalizing money laundering.\n*   **International Cooperation:**  There is significant international cooperation to combat money laundering, through treaties, information sharing, and joint investigations.\n*   **Financial Action Task Force (FATF):** The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) is an intergovernmental body that sets international standards for combating money laundering, terrorist financing, and other related threats to the integrity of the international financial system.  FATF's recommendations are widely adopted by countries around the world.\n\n**In summary:**\n\nMoney laundering is a serious offense with significant legal consequences.  It is a federal crime in the U.S. and a crime in most countries globally. It is actively combatted through legislation, regulation, and international cooperation. The goal is to disrupt criminal enterprises by depriving them of the ability to use the proceeds of their illegal activities.\n",
